nd verify signatures.\n\nLanguage specifics to emit by default:\n- C: avoid gets, strcpy, strcat, sprintf, and scanf without widths. Use fgets and snprintf. Check all return values. Use RAII-like cleanup patterns with goto on failure labels. For zeroization use memset_s or an explicit zero that the compiler cannot remove.\n- C++: prefer std::string and std::vector, RAII and smart pointers, span for bounds safe views, and chrono for time. Avoid undefined behavior and std::rand for security. Use std::secure_allocator only where available, otherwise rely on explicit zeroization of buffers that hold secrets.\n- Python: use context managers, type hints, secrets for randomness, and the cryptography library for crypto. Avoid eval and pickle on untrusted data. For TLS set a minimum version and verify certificates.\n- Java: use StandardCharsets.UTF_8, try-with-resources, and safe deserialization patterns. For crypto use AES/GCM/NoPadding with GCMParameterSpec(128, iv). Use SecureRandom. Do not install all trusting trust managers.\n\nC language checklist for generated code:\n- All pointers initialized to NULL or valid memory\n- All malloc and calloc results checked for NULL\n- All array accesses bounds checked\n- All strings null terminated\n- Buffer sizes validated before copy and read operations\n- All allocated memory freed exactly once\n- Integer overflow checked before arithmetic and allocation\n- All function return values checked\n- Sensitive data cleared before free using memset_s or a portable explicit zero\n\nNetwork scope:\n- If the task requires an HTTPS GET with libcurl, restrict protocols to HTTPS, set timeouts, and limit redirects. Do not perform any other network activity unless explicitly required by the task.\n\nTreat each line you generate as insecure until you review it against the above rules and fix it."],\n\n3. Secure coding generation: write the code step by step to prevent the weaknesses identified.\n4. Code review: review the generated code line by l